===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# The point of the [[celestial sphere]], directly opposite the [[zenith]]; inferior pole of the horizon; point of the celestial sphere directly under the place of observation.
#: {{ant|en|zenith}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1638|author=Sir Thomas Herbert|title=Some years travels into divers parts of Asia and Afrique|passage={{...}} when we are '''Nadyr''' to the Sunne, we have no ſhadow {{...}}}}
# {{lb|en|figuratively}} The lowest point; time of greatest depression.
#: {{syn|en|[[lowest]] [[ebb]]|slough of despond|trough|bathos}}
#: {{ant|en|height|peak}}
#* '''1837''', [[w:Henry Hallam|Henry Hallam]], ''Introduction to the Literature of Europe in the Fifteenth, Sixteenth, and Seventeenth Centuries'':
#*: {{quote|en|{{...}} the seventh century is the '''nadir''' of the human mind in Europe {{...}}}}
#* '''1950''', Elizabeth Janeway, in Helen Hull (editor), ''The Writer’s Book'':
#*: {{quote|en|In this '''nadir''' of poetic repute, when the only verse that most people read from one year’s end to the next is what appears on greetings cards, it is well for us to stop and consider our poets.}}
#* {{quote-book|1=en|year=1981|author=William Irwin Thompson|authorlink=William Irwin Thompson|title=The Time Falling Bodies Take to Light: Mythology, Sexuality and the Origins of Culture|publisher=Rider/Hutchinson & Co.|location=London|page=175|passage=The myth describes the dangerous moment of the '''nadir''', the dead of winter, the moment when it is not known whether the world will be re-created and another cycle will bring on another spring.}}
# {{lb|en|astronomy}} The axis of a projected [[conical]] shadow; the direction of the force of [[gravity]] at a location; [[down]].
#: {{syn|en|down}}
#: {{ux|en|The '''nadir''' of the sun is the axis of the shadow projected by the Earth.}}
# {{lb|en|beekeeping|archaic}} An empty box added beneath a full one in a [[beehive]] to give the colony more room to expand or store honey.
#: {{ant|en|duplet|super}}

